The UV–visible absorption and PL spectra of Ag@PCPDs were displayed in Fig. 3
                     a. Two major peaks in UV–visible absorption spectra obviously found at 285 nm and 344 nm is attributed to π–π* transition of the aromatic sp2 domain and n–π* transition caused by heteroatom doping of the Ag@PCPDs, respectively [26]. Moreover, it has the maximum emission wavelengths (Em
                     ) at 456 nm under the corresponding excitation (Ex
                     ) at 358 nm, with a PL quantum yield (QYs) of 15.6% (quinine sulfate as the standard). When placed under 365 nm UV light, the colorless Ag@PCPDs solutions displayed blue PL (inset of Fig. 3a). As depicted in Fig. 3b, the obtained CPDs materials show excitation-dependent PL behaviors, which might be ascribed to the π-conjugated systems in carbonized core and particle size distribution of CPDs [27]. What‘s more, the Ag@PCPDs were proved to have excellent stability in different pH condition (Fig. 3c) and ionic strength (Fig. 3d), demonstrating the adaptability of the synthesized Ag@PCPDs towards different environments. In addition, the PL intensity in Fig. S3a had no salient change after one month, indicating the photostability of the Ag@PCPDs.
